.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Signer \- Construct a signature for any transaction
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 6
\&        # sign a multisignature transaction
\&        $tx\->sign(signing_index => 0, script => $p2ms_script, %more_args)
\&                \->add_signature($priv, SIGHASH_ALL)
\&                \->add_signature(\*(Aqbytestring signature\*(Aq)
\&                \->finalize_multisignature
\&                \->finalize;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class implements a signer for transactions of any complexity. It is best
used for custom transactions which cannot be signed by calling
"sign_transaction" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private.
.PP
It works by running the script in the background, progressing it with each
added signature. Executing the script allows finding the correct
signature\-checking opcodes to sign by simulating how the script will behave
when the transaction is verified. No changes to the underlying transaction are
applied until the signature is finalized.
.PP
Note that since transactions use stack as a data structure, the order of
generated signature will be reversed, which may be surprising when inspecting
the transaction. Method calls must be done in order of opcode execution.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
Attributes vary depending on signing output type.
.SS "Common attributes"
.IX Subsection "Common attributes"
These attributes are common for all output types.
.PP
\fItransaction\fR
.IX Subsection "transaction"
.PP
Mandatory transaction object. No need to include it when calling
"sign" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction, because it will be included
automatically.
.PP
\fIsigning_index\fR
.IX Subsection "signing_index"
.PP
The index of input being signed. Required.
.PP
\fIscript\fR
.IX Subsection "script"
.PP
The script being signed. It is required for script hash output types (\f(CW\*(C`P2SH\*(C'\fR
and \f(CW\*(C`P2WSH\*(C'\fR). Otherwise it will be taken from output locking script. In
taproot script spends, it will be taken from "script_tree" and "leaf_id".
.SS "Taproot attributes"
.IX Subsection "Taproot attributes"
These attributes are only used for taproot outputs.
.PP
\fIscript_tree\fR
.IX Subsection "script_tree"
.PP
Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Tree instance with a script tree used when creating
the taproot output. Must be passed for script spends or key spends with enabled
script path.
.PP
\fIleaf_id\fR
.IX Subsection "leaf_id"
.PP
Numeric identifier which marks the leaf in "script_tree". Must be passed for
script spends.
.PP
\fIpublic_key\fR
.IX Subsection "public_key"
.PP
A taproot internal key which was used for creating this output. Must be passed
for script spends.
.PP
\fItaproot_ext_flag\fR
.IX Subsection "taproot_ext_flag"
.PP
A taproot extension flag for script spends. By default, a value \f(CW1\fR (for
tapscript) is used.
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer = $class\->new(%args)
.Ve
.PP
This is a standard Moo constructor, which can be used to create the object. It
takes arguments specified in "Common attributes" and "Taproot attributes".
Usually, there is no need to call this method directly, as it will be called by
"sign" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction on the correct Signer subclass.
.PP
Returns class instance.
.PP
\fIadd_bytes\fR
.IX Subsection "add_bytes"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer = $signer\->add_bytes($bytestr)
.Ve
.PP
Adds raw bytes from \f(CW$bytestr\fR into the signature. Note that this should not
be used to add signatures \- use "add_signature" with bytes instead.
.PP
Returns the instance, for chaining.
.PP
\fIadd_number\fR
.IX Subsection "add_number"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer = $signer\->add_number($num)
.Ve
.PP
Adds a script number \f(CW$num\fR into the signature.
.PP
Returns the instance, for chaining.
.PP
\fIadd_signature\fR
.IX Subsection "add_signature"
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        $signer = $signer\->add_signature($bytestr, %args)
\&        $signer = $signer\->add_signature($privkey, %args)
.Ve
.PP
Adds a signature to the transaction. If \f(CW$privkey\fR is passed
(Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private), then it will be used to sign the next
signature\-checking opcode in the script. If \f(CW$bytestr\fR is passed, then it will
be used as\-is, but unlike "add_bytes", next call to \f(CW\*(C`add_signature\*(C'\fR will
correctly target next opcode.
.PP
If the next signature\-checking opcode is a multisig, then it will not step over
it after the call, but wait for a mandatory "finalize_multisignature" call.
.PP
\&\f(CW%args\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`sighash\*(C'\fR
.Sp
The sighash which should be used for the signature. By default "SIGHASH_ALL" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants
is used for pre\-taproot outputs and "SIGHASH_DEFAULT" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants for taproot
outputs.
.PP
Returns the instance, for chaining.
.PP
\fIfinalize_multisignature\fR
.IX Subsection "finalize_multisignature"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer = $signer\->finalize_multisignature()
.Ve
.PP
Used to finalize signing of multisig opcodes. It is mandatory to call it when
signing a multisig transaction.
.PP
Returns the instance, for chaining.
.PP
\fIfinalize\fR
.IX Subsection "finalize"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signer\->finalize()
.Ve
.PP
Finalizes the signing process, applying changes on the transaction object.
After this call, the \f(CW$signer\fR object is done and should be discarded as soon
as possible.
.PP
Returns nothing, as the signing process is done.
